&gt; Jeff, first, if fitness is stagnant, then the system should be increasing the
&gt; average number of nodes (though not necessarily the number of nodes in the
&gt; champ).  In a stagnant situation, you do not have information (i.e. a
&gt; gradient) suggesting which direction is right to go.  Therefore, the most
&gt; principled response is to expand your options while never putting all your
&gt; eggs in one basket.  When fitness is stagnant, we cannot know if further
&gt; search within the currently dimensionality might eventually find a solution,
&gt; or if the current dimensionality is insufficient and contains no solution at
&gt; all.  In the latter case, the number of nodes and connections would need to
&gt; ascend to higher dimensionality.  Because we do not know which case we are in
&gt; when stagnation occurs, the best idea is to try both:  Some species start
&gt; arriving with bigger networks while others keep searching in the same old
&gt; spaces.  Thus, we would expect the *range* of sizes to increase along with the
&gt; average size.  
&gt; 
&gt; Your situation with nondeterminism is probably somewhat similar, causing the
&gt; average size of solutions to go up because of stagnation.  However, because
&gt; the champion will keep changing with the randomized evaluation, you will
&gt; observe this phenomenon in the champion itself.  The more noisy it is, the
&gt; more it is probably observable (i.e. because the more &quot;random&quot; it is who
&gt; happens to look best at any given time, in effect leading to a kind of
&gt; sampling of the population through the champion).
&gt; 
&gt; Of course, that may not be a complete explanation for the steep angle of the
&gt; incline.  I would guess that nondeterminism is also causing a general
&gt; unhealthiness about the evolutionary process overall. Nondeterminism is highly
&gt; destructive to evolutionary algorithms.  This issue is controversial (even
&gt; within my own group!) but my personal opinion is one should avoid
&gt; nondeterminism unless it is absolutely essential.  For example, you can choose
&gt; a random order of examples but then subject everyone to the same random set -
&gt; a kind of &quot;deterministic randomness.&quot;  Of course, you are banking on the
&gt; impartiality of randomness to give you maximal generality, but it will often
&gt; be outweighed by its unhealthy side effects on the population.  So I&#39;m
&gt; guessing that part of the phenomenon is just a side-effect of an inconsistent
&gt; evaluation scheme leading to relative chaos.
&gt; 
&gt; There may also be more to it; it merits further investigation as well.
